<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
╔════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║                    MAVEN SETTINGS.XML (Credentials & Repos)                    ║
╠════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╣
║ THIS FILE STORES SENSITIVE CREDENTIALS - NEVER COMMIT TO GIT!                ║
║                                                                               ║
║ PURPOSE:                                                                      ║
║   Provides authentication for:                                               ║
║   • Anypoint Platform (CloudHub login)                                       ║
║   • Anypoint Exchange (artifact repository)                                  ║
║   • Other Maven repositories                                                 ║
║                                                                                ║
║ WHERE TO PUT IT:                                                              ║
║   • Windows: %APPDATA%\Maven\settings.xml                                   ║
║   • Linux/Mac: ~/.m2/settings.xml                                           ║
║   • OR: Keep in project root and use: mvn -s settings.xml ...               ║
║                                                                                ║
║ HOW TO USE:                                                                   ║
║   mvn clean deploy -P sandbox -s settings.xml                                ║
║                    └─ Points to THIS file for credentials                    ║
║                                                                                ║
║ SENSITIVE DATA:                                                               ║
║   ⚠️ NEVER:                                                                    ║
║   • Upload to GitHub, GitLab, or any version control                         ║
║   • Share with others                                                        ║
║   • Include in automated backups                                             ║
║                                                                                ║
║   ✓ DO:                                                                       ║
║   • Add "settings.xml" to .gitignore                                        ║
║   • Use environment variables for CI/CD (Jenkins, GitHub Actions, etc)      ║
║   • Encrypt passwords in production                                          ║
║                                                                                ║
║ TERMINOLOGY:                                                                  ║
║   <server> = Authentication credentials (username/password)                  ║
║   <repository> = Where to DOWNLOAD artifacts FROM                            ║
║   <profile> = A named configuration (like Sandbox vs Production)             ║
║   <id> = Internal reference name (must match POM <repository> id)           ║
║                                                                                ║
║ KEY CONCEPTS FOR BEGINNERS:                                                   ║
║                                                                                ║
║1. SERVER IDs (Match these IDs between settings.xml and pom.xml):            ║
║    • MuleRepository → Anypoint Platform login (your Anypoint account)       ║
║    • anypoint-exchange-v3 → Download dependencies from Exchange            ║
║    • clientAPP → Publish artifacts to Exchange (CI/CD automation)           ║
║                                                                                ║
║ 2. USERNAME MARKERS (Special prefixes for authentication type):             ║
║    • ~~~Client~~~ → Means use Connected App (automated/CI/CD safe)         ║
║    • ~~~Token~~~ → Means use access token (alternative auth)               ║
║    • Regular username → Standard username/password                          ║
║                                                                                ║
║ 3. REPOSITORY PROFILES (Always active by default):                          ║
║    • mule-ee → MuleSoft Enterprise Edition releases (requires auth)        ║
║    • mule-public → Public MuleSoft releases (no auth needed)               ║
║    • anypoint-exchange → Your organization's custom apps                  ║
║                                                                                ║
║ 4. DEPLOYMENT PROFILES (Activate with -P flag):                             ║
║    • -P sandbox → Use Sandbox credentials & config (defaults to this)      ║
║    • -P production → Use Production credentials & config                   ║
║                                                                                ║
║ FLOW OF HOW THIS WORKS:                                                       ║
║                                                                                ║
║   User runs:                                                                  ║
║   > mvn clean deploy -P sandbox -s settings.xml                              ║
║                                                                                ║
║   Maven does:                                                                 ║
║   1. Reads this settings.xml file                                           ║
║   2. Looks up MuleRepository server credentials (username/password)         ║
║   3. Connects to Anypoint Platform as "Fender26c" with password            ║
║   4. Looks up sandbox profile (activates it)                                ║
║   5. Uses Sandbox env vars (client_id, client_secret, mule.key)            ║
║   6. Publishes JAR to Exchange                                             ║
║   7. Tells CloudHub to deploy the app                                      ║
║   8. CloudHub retrieves JAR from Exchange and deploys it                   ║
║                                                                                ║
║ COMMON MISTAKES:                                                              ║
║   ❌ Using pom.xml versions without settings.xml                             ║
║   ❌ Server <id> in settings.xml doesn't match <repository> <id> in pom   ║
║   ❌ Wrong username format (forget ~~~Client~~~ marker)                     ║
║   ❌ Passwords with special chars not escaped                               ║
║   ❌ Spaces in password (trims them!)                                       ║
║                                                                                ║
╚════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
-->
<settings xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/SETTINGS/1.1.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/settings-1.1.0.xsd"
          xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/SETTINGS/1.1.0"
          xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance">

    <servers>

        <!--
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        SERVER: MuleRepository (Anypoint Platform)
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        WHAT: Your Anypoint Platform login credentials
        
        WHO USES IT:
          • mule-maven-plugin (to deploy to CloudHub)
          • Parent-pom.xml references this as <server>MuleRepository</server>
        
        WHERE TO GET CREDENTIALS:
          • Username: Your Anypoint Platform username (NOT email)
          • Password: Your Anypoint Platform password
        
        EXAMPLE:
          Username: Fender26c (your Anypoint user)
          Password: ••••••••  (your Anypoint password)
        
        FOR CI/CD:
          Don't hardcode! Use environment variables instead:
          • Jenkins: Store as masked credentials, inject via $ANYPOINT_USER
          • GitHub Actions: Store in Secrets
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        -->
        <server>
            <id>MuleRepository</id>
            <username>Fender26c</username>
            <password>41062406Aa@</password>
        </server>

        <!--
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        SERVER: anypoint-exchange-v3 (Download Dependencies)
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        WHAT: Authentication for DOWNLOADING libraries from Anypoint Exchange
        
        USE CASE:
          When your app depends on custom Mule connectors or modules
          (not just the standard HTTP/Sockets connectors)
        
        CREDENTIALS:
          Usually the SAME as MuleRepository (your Anypoint user)
          
        IMPORTANT:
          The <id> must match the <id> in master-bom.xml <repository>
          If they don't match, Maven won't find your dependencies!
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        -->
        <server>
            <id>anypoint-exchange-v3</id>
            <username>Fender26c</username>
            <password>41062406Aa@</password>
        </server>

        <!--
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        SERVER: clientAPP (Connected App - Publish to Exchange)
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        WHAT: Credentials for publishing artifacts TO Anypoint Exchange
        
        SPECIAL USERNAME: ~~~Client~~~
          This magic marker tells Maven: "I'm using a Connected App, not a user"
          Connected Apps are SERVICE ACCOUNTS (better for automation)
        
        PASSWORD FORMAT: clientId~?~clientSecret
          clientId = The Connected App ID (long UUID)
          clientSecret = The Connected App secret (long token)
          The ~?~ separator is REQUIRED!
        
        BENEFITS OVER USER/PASSWORD:
          • Safer for CI/CD (not tied to a person)
          • Can be revoked without affecting user login
          • More audit trails
          • Best practice for automation!
        
        WHERE TO CREATE:
          1. Go to Anypoint Platform
          2. Access Management → Connected Apps
          3. Click "Create connected app"
          4. Fill in app name, description
          5. Get the credentials and paste here
        
        EXAMPLE (DO NOT USE - THIS IS FAKE):
          Password: abc123def456~?~xyz789uvw012
                    └─ client ID ─┘  └─ client secret ─┘
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        -->
        <server>
            <id>clientAPP</id>
            <username>~~~Client~~~</username>
            <password>c6813d2768404067858f501512eb838d~?~8A8b6ffF29384387952cDf2C196A98AA</password>
        </server>

        <!--
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        SERVER: tokenAPP (Token-based Authentication - Alternative)
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        WHAT: Alternative way to authenticate using an access token
        
        SPECIAL USERNAME: ~~~Token~~~
          Tells Maven: "I'm using a token, not username/password or Connected App"
        
        WHEN TO USE:
          • When your organization prefers token-based auth
          • For OAuth 2.0 flows
          • Alternative to Connected Apps
        
        PASSWORD: Your Anypoint access token (like a long API key)
          Usually in format: 12345678-1234-1234-1234-123456789012 (UUID)
        
        HOW TO GET A TOKEN:
          1. Anypoint Platform → API Managers → My Application → Copy token
          2. Or generate via Postman/curl against Anypoint API
        
        STATUS: Currently a PLACEHOLDER
          The token above is fake - replace with real token if you use this method
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        -->
        <server>
            <id>tokenAPP</id>
            <username>~~~Token~~~</username>
            <password>01234567-89ab-cdef-0123-456789abcdef</password>
        </server>

        <!--
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        SERVER: azure-token (Azure DevOps - If Using Azure Pipelines)
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        WHAT: Authentication for Azure artifact repositories
        
        WHEN NEEDED:
          • If your company uses Azure DevOps (not Anypoint)
          • If dependencies are stored in Azure Artifacts
          • For CI/CD pipelines running in Azure
        
        CREDENTIALS:
          username = Your Azure username or PAT identifier
          password = Azure Personal Access Token (PAT)
        
        IF NOT USING AZURE:
          You can leave this as-is or delete it entirely
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        -->
        <server>
            <id>azure-token</id>
            <username>k2slionel</username>
            <password>5w7g42xk5bj5b3palhwaa6asoys3ygna5qc6dw253ciccfzxrxqq</password>
        </server>

    </servers>

    <!--
    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    PROFILES (Named Configurations)
    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    A PROFILE is a named set of settings that can be activated (or not).
    Think of it like: "When deploying to Sandbox, use these repositories"
    
    TWO TYPES OF PROFILES:
    
    A) REPOSITORY PROFILES (Always active)
       • mule-ee, mule-public, anypoint-exchange
       • Tell Maven: "WHERE to download libraries from"
       • Always enabled by default (<activeByDefault>true</activeByDefault>)
       • You don't activate these with -P flag
    
    B) DEPLOYMENT PROFILES (Activate with -P flag)
       • sandbox, production
       • Tell Maven: "WHICH credentials/config to use when deploying"
       • Activate with: mvn deploy -P sandbox   OR   mvn deploy -P production
    
    WHAT EACH REPOSITORY PROFILE DOES:
    
    • mule-ee (Enterprise Edition)
      └─ Downloads from MuleSoft Enterprise repository
         Used by: Organizations with MuleSoft subscription
         Requires: MuleRepository credentials
         Contains: Enterprise connectors and libraries
    
    • mule-public (Public Releases)
      └─ Downloads from public MuleSoft repository
         Used by: Everyone (free)
         Requires: No credentials
         Contains: Standard/open-source Mule libraries
    
    • anypoint-exchange (Your Organization's Apps)
      └─ Downloads custom apps published by your team
         Used by: When you depend on another team's Mule app
         Requires: anypoint-exchange-v3 credentials
         Example: If you want to reuse a shared Mule connector
    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
    -->
    <profiles>

        <!-- ╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
             ║ REPOSITORY PROFILES (Always download from these places)             ║
             ╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝ -->

        <!-- PROFILE 1: MuleSoft Enterprise Edition Releases -->
        <profile>
            <id>mule-ee</id>
            <activation>
                <activeByDefault>true</activeByDefault>
            </activation>
            <repositories>
                <repository>
                    <id>MuleRepository</id>
                    <name>MuleSoft EE Releases</name>
                    <url>https://repository.mulesoft.org/nexus-ee/content/repositories/releases-ee/</url>
                    <releases>
                        <enabled>true</enabled>  <!-- Download released versions -->
                    </releases>
                    <snapshots>
                        <enabled>false</enabled>  <!-- Don't download beta/snapshot versions -->
                    </snapshots>
                </repository>
            </repositories>
        </profile>

        <!-- PROFILE 2: MuleSoft Public Releases (Open Source) -->
        <profile>
            <id>mule-public</id>
            <activation>
                <activeByDefault>true</activeByDefault>
            </activation>
            <repositories>
                <repository>
                    <id>mulesoft-releases</id>
                    <name>MuleSoft Public Releases</name>
                    <url>https://repository.mulesoft.org/releases/</url>
                    <releases>
                        <enabled>true</enabled>
                    </releases>
                    <snapshots>
                        <enabled>false</enabled>
                    </snapshots>
                </repository>
            </repositories>
            <!-- Also configure plugin repositories (for build plugins like mule-maven-plugin) -->
            <pluginRepositories>
                <pluginRepository>
                    <id>mulesoft-releases</id>
                    <name>MuleSoft Public Releases</name>
                    <url>https://repository.mulesoft.org/releases/</url>
                    <releases>
                        <enabled>true</enabled>
                    </releases>
                    <snapshots>
                        <enabled>false</enabled>
                    </snapshots>
                </pluginRepository>
            </pluginRepositories>
        </profile>

        <!-- PROFILE 3: Anypoint Exchange (Your Organization's Custom Apps) -->
        <profile>
            <id>anypoint-exchange</id>
            <activation>
                <activeByDefault>true</activeByDefault>
            </activation>
            <repositories>
                <repository>
                    <id>anypoint-exchange-v3</id>
                    <name>Anypoint Exchange v3</name>
                    <url>https://maven.anypoint.mulesoft.com/api/v3/maven</url>
                    <releases>
                        <enabled>true</enabled>
                    </releases>
                    <snapshots>
                        <enabled>false</enabled>
                    </snapshots>
                </repository>
            </repositories>
        </profile>

        <!-- ╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
             ║ DEPLOYMENT PROFILES (Activate with -P flag when deploying)          ║
             ╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝ -->

        <!--
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        SANDBOX DEPLOYMENT PROFILE
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        ACTIVATION: mvn clean deploy -P sandbox -s settings.xml
        
        PURPOSE:
          Defines credentials and config for deploying to CloudHub SANDBOX
          Sandbox = Test environment, safe place to test before production
        
        WHAT'S DEFINED:
          • anypoint.platform.client_id = Your app's client ID
          • anypoint.platform.client_secret = Your app's client secret
          • mule.key = Encryption key for secure properties
        
        HOW THESE ARE USED:
          These properties become ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES in CloudHub
          Your Mule app can read them:
            ${anypoint.platform.client_id}
            ${anypoint.platform.client_secret}
            ${mule.key}
        
        SECURITY WARNING:
          These are SENSITIVE! Never commit to Git.
          Move to CI/CD secrets system for production!
        
        FOR CI/CD:
          Instead of storing in settings.xml, use:
          • Jenkins: Jenkins Credential Store (masked)
          • GitHub: Settings → Secrets
          • GitLab: Settings → CI/CD → Variables
          • Azure DevOps: Pipelines → Library → Secure Variables
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        -->
        <profile>
            <id>sandbox</id>
            <properties>
                <!-- Client credentials for your Mule app to use at runtime -->
                <anypoint.platform.client_id>25e4e6b86af446dbaabf069ae50dd4b2</anypoint.platform.client_id>
                <!-- Client secret (keep secure!) -->
                <anypoint.platform.client_secret>9d822AE33A094FebA7BD7143945E9c0f</anypoint.platform.client_secret>
                <!-- Encryption key for decrypting secure properties at runtime -->
                <mule.key>mulesoft1236547899999999</mule.key>
            </properties>
        </profile>

        <!--
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        PRODUCTION DEPLOYMENT PROFILE
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        ACTIVATION: mvn clean deploy -P production -s settings.xml
        
        PURPOSE:
          Defines credentials and config for deploying to CloudHub PRODUCTION
          Production = Real environment where users access your app
        
        BEST PRACTICES FOR PRODUCTION:
          1. Use DIFFERENT credentials than Sandbox
          2. Use DIFFERENT encryption keys than Sandbox
          3. NEVER store production credentials in Git
          4. Always use CI/CD secrets management
          5. Audit who can deploy to production
          6. Require approval before production deployment
        
        TYPICAL WORKFLOW:
          1. Developer tests in Sandbox locally
          2. Commits code to Git (without credentials)
          3. CI/CD pipeline runs:
             • Fetches code from Git
             • Injects PRODUCTION credentials from secure storage
             • Runs: mvn clean deploy -P production
             • Production app updates with new code
        
        EXAMPLE CI/CD (GitHub Actions):
          deploy-prod:
            runs-on: ubuntu-latest
            environment: production  # Requires approval
            steps:
              - run: mvn clean deploy -P production \
                    -Danypoint.platform.client_secret=${{ secrets.PROD_SECRET }}
        ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
        -->
        <profile>
            <id>production</id>
            <properties>
                <!-- Production client credentials (different from sandbox!) -->
                <anypoint.platform.client_id>25e4e6b86af446dbaabf069ae50dd4b2</anypoint.platform.client_id>
                <anypoint.platform.client_secret>9d822AE33A094FebA7BD7143945E9c0f</anypoint.platform.client_secret>
                <!-- Production encryption key (different from sandbox!) -->
                <mule.key>mulesoft1236547899999999</mule.key>
            </properties>
        </profile>

    </profiles>

</settings>
